<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Basic Search Review :</strong></p>
<h6 id=3D"MonitoringinwestpacMesh-SplunkSearchProcessingLanguage(SPL):"><sp=
an style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Splunk Search Processing Languag=
e (SPL):</strong></span></h6>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">It is the language used to perform=
 searches against the indexed data. With its versatile SQL like and Unix pi=
pe syntax, SPL offers a very powerful way to explore and investigate your <=
br>
 machine data.</span></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,255)=
;"><em><u><strong>WATCH SPL INTRODUCTION VIDEO :&nbsp;</strong></u></em></s=
pan> &nbsp;<a href=3D"/download/attachments/1211649003/SPL_Intro.mp4?versio=
n=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1681343442330&amp;api=3Dv2" data-linked-resour=
ce-id=3D"1359032406" data-linked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resourc=
e-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-default-alias=3D"SPL_Intro.mp4" =
data-nice-type=3D"Multimedia" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"video/mp=
4" data-linked-resource-container-id=3D"1211649003" data-linked-resource-co=
ntainer-version=3D"66">SPL_Intro.mp4</a>( 1.5 Min)</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Syntax of SPL:</strong></s=
pan></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">The Search Processing Language is =
a hybrid of SQL (Structured Query Language) and Unix pipe. Just like any ot=
her query language, SPL follows certain syntax. When a query has a syntax e=
rror, it does not execute, and an error is shown indicating the problem wit=
h <br>
 the syntax. Let us take a look at the general syntax of SPL. An SPL query =
can consist of any or all of the following.<br></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Commands :</strong></span>=
</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102=
);">Commands are keywords that execute certain functionality in Splunk. A b=
asic (yet very powerful) command in Splunk is search. Commands can accept o=
ne or more parameters. Here are some examples of commands:</span></span></p=
>
<p><br></p>
<ol>
<li style=3D"font-weight: bold;"><strong>table</strong></li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 40.0px;"><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: Th=
e table command formats search results into a table with only the specified=
 fields.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 40.0px;"><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: <span s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">| <em>table field1, field2, ...</em></span=
></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 40.0px;"><strong><em>Example</em></strong>: <em><s=
pan style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | table apiname &n=
bsp;app_correlation_id message_id</span></em></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 40.0px;"><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: Th=
is command displays apiname &nbsp;app_correlation_id and message_id fields =
in a table format, excluding all other fields from the output.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 40.0px;"><br></p>
<p>2. <strong>stats</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The stats command aggregates data=
 using various statistical functions such as count, sum, avg, min, max, etc=
. It groups the results by specified fields.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>:<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);"=
> | stats function(field) by field1, field2, ...</span></p>
<p><strong><em>Example</em></strong>:<strong>&nbsp;</strong><em><span style=
=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | stats count by status</sp=
an></em></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command counts the number of=
 events for each unique status code and displays the result.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>3. <strong>eval</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The eval command creates or modif=
ies fields using expressions or functions. It allows for the computation of=
 new values or transformation of existing ones.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: |&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,10=
2,255);">eval new_field=3Dexpression</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>: <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255)=
;">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | eval response_time_ms=3Dresponse_time &nbsp;1000</s=
pan></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command creates a new field =
called response_time_ms, which is the response_time field converted from se=
conds to milliseconds.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>4. <strong>timechart</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The timechart command creates tim=
e-based charts and aggregations, automatically grouping data by time interv=
als.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: |&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,10=
2,255);">timechart span=3Dinterval function(field) [by field2, ...]</span><=
/p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>:&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102=
,255);">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | timechart span=3D1h avg(response_time)</span><=
/p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command generates a time-bas=
ed chart showing the average response_time for each 1-hour interval.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>5. rename</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The rename command changes the na=
me of a field in the search results.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>:| <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255)=
;">rename old_field as new_field</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>:&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102=
,255);">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | rename response_time as rt</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command renames the field re=
sponse_time to rt in the search results.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>6. fields</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The fields command includes or ex=
cludes specific fields from the search results.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>:</p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">|fields +field1, +field2, ...&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (to include fields)</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">|fields -field1, -field2, ...&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (to exclude fields)</span></p>
<p><strong>Example</strong>: <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">index=
=3Dprd_a008e0 | fields host, status</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command includes only the ho=
st and status fields in the results, excluding all others.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>7. dedup</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The dedup command removes duplica=
te events based on the values of specified fields, keeping only the first o=
ccurrence.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax:</strong></em></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">| dedup field1, field2, ...</spa=
n></p>
<p><em><strong>Example: </strong></em><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255)=
;">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | dedup user_ip</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command removes duplicate ev=
ents based on the user_ip field, keeping only the first event for each uniq=
ue user_ip</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>8. sort</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The sort command arranges search =
results in ascending or descending order based on specified fields.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>:</p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);">| sort [+|-]field1, [+|-]field2,=
 ...</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Example: </strong></em><span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255)=
;">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | sort -response_time</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Explanation</strong></em>: This command sorts the results by=
 response_time in descending order.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>9. <strong>where</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The where command filters results=
 based on a condition or expression.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: | <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255=
);">where condition</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>:&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102=
,255);">index=3Dprd_a008e0 | where response_time &gt; 500</span></p>
<p><strong>Explanation</strong>: This command filters events where response=
_time is greater than 500 milliseconds.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>10. <strong>top</strong></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The top command lists the most co=
mmon values for a specified field and provides counts and percentages.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: top field [limit=3Dn]</p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>: index=3Dprd_a008e0 | top status</p>
<p><strong>Explanation</strong>: This command shows the most frequent statu=
s codes and their counts, providing a summary of the top values.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>11. <strong>chart</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The chart command creates charts =
based on aggregated data without necessarily being time-based.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: chart function(field) over field1 [by =
field2, ...]</p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>: index=3Dprd_a008e0 | chart avg(respon=
se_time) by status</p>
<p><strong>Explanation</strong>: This command creates a chart showing the a=
verage response_time for each status code.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>12. <strong>transaction</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The transaction command groups ev=
ents into transactions based on common fields and optional time constraints=
.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: transaction field [startswith=3D"start=
_event" endswith=3D"end_event" maxspan=3Dduration]</p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>: index=3Dprd_a008e0 | transaction sess=
ion_id startswith=3D"login" endswith=3D"logout"</p>
<p><strong>Explanation</strong>: This command groups events by session_id, =
considering each group to start with a "login" event and end with a "logout=
" event.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>12. <strong>Lookup</strong></p>
<p><em><strong>Description</strong></em>: The <code>lookup</code> command a=
llows you to reference external lookup tables to add additional fields to y=
our search results based on matching values.</p>
<p><em><strong>Syntax</strong></em>: <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255);=
">| lookup lookup_table_name field_to_match AS field_to_match_in_lookup OUT=
PUT new_field1, new_field2, ...</span></p>
<p><em><strong>Example</strong></em>: <span style=3D"color: rgb(51,102,255)=
;">index=3Dtest_idx | lookup ip_lookup ip AS client_ip OUTPUT location, hos=
tname</span></p>
<p><strong>Explanation</strong>:&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li><strong><code>lookup ip_lookup</code></strong>: Specifies the name of t=
he lookup table. In this example, <code>ip_lookup</code> is the name of the=
 lookup table.</li>
<li><strong><code>ip AS client_ip</code></strong>: Specifies the field in y=
our search results (<code>client_ip</code>) that you want to match with a f=
ield in the lookup table (<code>ip</code>).</li>
<li><strong><code>OUTPUT location, hostname</code></strong>: Defines the fi=
elds from the lookup table that you want to add to your search results. In =
this case, <code>location</code> and <code>hostname</code> are the new fiel=
ds added from the lookup table.</li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Note:=E2=80=83At the start of an S=
PL query, the search command is implied so you don=E2=80=99t need to explic=
itly type it. The search command must be specified if it comes later in the=
 search pipeline.<br></span></p>
<p><br></p>
