<p><br></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Literal Strings</strong><b=
r>
 You can search for any string or phrase. If the phrase has spaces, you nee=
d to enclose the phrase in double quotes. Here are some examples of searchi=
ng for literal strings:<br></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Error</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">i/o Exception</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">=E2=80=9Cjava.lang.NullPointerExc=
eption=E2=80=9D</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">=E2=80=9COrder processed successf=
ully=E2=80=9D</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">=E2=80=9CProgram quit unexpectedl=
y=E2=80=9D<br></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Key-Value Pairs:</strong><=
/span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><br>
 When Splunk indexes the data, it converts raw data into searchable events.=
 During the process, it extracts certain key-value pairs and stores them as=
 fields. These fields are generally the default fields such as host, source=
, and sourcetypes. Fields can also be <br>
 extracted during search-time. You can use these fields to filter your data=
. Using key-value pairs is one of the most basic yet significant ways of se=
arching your data. The key must be a field in the events. Here are some exa=
mples of key-value pairs:<br></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">index =3D main</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">sourcetype =3D userPortal:app:err=
orLog</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">status =3D 500</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">result =3D =E2=80=9COrder process=
ed successfully=E2=80=9D</span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">log_level =3D ERROR<br></span></l=
i>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Note If the field name contains s=
paces, use single quotes around them, for example, =E2=80=98user id=E2=80=
=99 =3D jsmith.<br></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><strong>Wildcard:</strong></span><=
/p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">You can use the wildcard asterisk =
(*) to match zero or more of any character. This is the only wildcard suppo=
rted when used in literal strings and as part of key-value pairs. Here are =
some examples of using wildcard:<br></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">status =3D 5* =E2=86=90 Retrieves=
 events that have status starting with 5. For example, 500, 503, and 504<br=
></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"http://=
java.net" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">java.net</a>.Connection*=
=E2=80=9D =E2=86=90 Retrieves events that have the string&nbsp;<a href=3D"h=
ttp://java.net" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">jaa.net</a>.Connec=
tion followed by zero or more of any character. For example, <a href=3D"htt=
p://java.net" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">java.net</a>.Connect=
ionRefused, <a href=3D"http://java.net" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofo=
llow">java.net</a>.ConnectionTimedOut<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">=E2=80=9CLogin for user*failed=E2=
=80=9D =E2=86=90 Retrieves events that have the string =E2=80=9CLogin for u=
ser=E2=80=9D followed by zero or more of any character, followed by the str=
ing =E2=80=9Cfailed=E2=80=9D<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;=E2=80=9CAccount number:*ac=
tivated=E2=80=9D =E2=86=90 Retrieves events that have the string =E2=80=9CA=
ccount number:* followed by zero or more of any character, followed by the =
string =E2=80=9Cactivated=E2=80=9D</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Note=E2=80=83Using the * wildcard =
as the first character in a string is very inefficient. For example, avoid =
searching for strings like =E2=80=9C*error=E2=80=9D.<br>
 &nbsp;</span></p>
<p><strong>Booleans :</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 90.0px;">NOT, OR, AND is implied; MUST be uppercas=
e; can use ( )'s to force precedence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 90.0px;">sourcetype=3D&lt;A&gt; OR (sourcetype=3DB=
 user=3Dxyz)</p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><u>Here are some examples of using=
 Boolean:</u></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;log_level =3D WARNING OR lo=
g_level =3D ERROR<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;result =3D Failed AND user =
=3D jsmith<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;output =3D =E2=80=9CLogin s=
ucceeded=E2=80=9D NOT admin<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;result =3D Error OR (result=
 =3D Pass AND response_time &gt; 500)<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Note=E2=80=83The Boolean operator=
s must be in uppercase. You can also use parenthesis to force precedence. <=
/span></li>
</ul>
<h4 id=3D"MonitoringinwestpacMesh-Functions:"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,5=
1,102);"><strong>Functions :</strong></span></h4>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);"><br>
 Many SPL commands have functions that you can utilize when using those com=
mands. Functions typically operate on parameters you specify. </span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">Here are some examples of SPL func=
tions:</span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">=E2=80=A6| stats avg(response_tim=
e). =E2=86=90 Calculates the average response time<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;=E2=80=A6| timechart perc95=
(processingTime) =E2=86=90 Calculates the 95th percentile of processingTime=
<br></span></li>
<li><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,51,102);">&nbsp;=E2=80=A6. | eval percentSu=
ccess =3D round(success_rate,2) =E2=86=90 Rounds the success_rate to two de=
cimal places and stores the result in a new filed percentSuccess</span></li=
>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Comparisons</strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">=3D, !=3D, &lt;, &lt;=3D, &gt;=3D, &gt; s=
tatus&gt;399, user!=3D admin</p>
