/p>
<p>How to check when the ingestion stopped for a host or source or sourcety=
pes.</p>
<p><strong>Summary :</strong></p>
<p>1. The key to fast searches is moving as little data as possible.</p>
<p>2. Time range is the most powerful lever you have to control the amount =
of data being moved.</p>
<p>3. Not all searches need to be tuned. Focus on frequently used searches =
and searches that retrieve large amounts of data.</p>
<p>4. Use the search modes in the following order =E2=80=93 fast, smart, an=
d verbose =E2=80=93 to meet your needs. When you save a search, the search =
mode is preserved.</p>
<p>5. Filter as much data as possible before the first pipe in the SPL quer=
y.</p>
<p>6. When scheduling searches, make use of the automatic schedule window.<=
/p>
<p>7. Utilise report acceleration, data model acceleration, and summary ind=
exing for searching against large amounts of data. Important sections of se=
arch job parameters in job inspector<br>
 Search job parameter Description optimized Search The restructured search =
based on built-in search optimiser. Splunk automatically moves commands aro=
und to make the search faster scanCount Number of events read resultCount N=
umber of results returned</p>
<p>8. Data model acceleration is more efficient than report acceleration an=
d summary indexing.</p>
<p>9. Use job inspector to analyse the execution costs of various parts of =
your SPL query.</p>
<p>10. Rearrange the components of the SPL query so that distributable stre=
aming commands are placed before any transforming</p>
<p><strong>Key Dashboards walkthrough : ??</strong></p>
<h4 id=3D"MonitoringinwestpacMesh-AdvancedSplunkLearningsources:">Advanced =
Splunk Learning sources:</h4>
